diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder that results in recurrent episodes of severe swelling (angioedema).

diagnoses.name: Allergic Reaction
diagnoses.description: A hypersensitivity reaction to a particular allergen; symptoms can range from mild to severe and include angioedema.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Disorders
diagnoses.description: Conditions in which the body's immune system mistakenly attacks its own tissues, potentially causing various symptoms including dyshydrotic eczema and easy bruising.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Idiopathic Urticaria
diagnoses.description: A condition where hives or swelling occur without a known cause, which can include symptoms like angioedema and easy bruising.

diagnoses.name: Contact Dermatitis
diagnoses.description: A type of inflammation of the skin resulting from direct contact with an irritant or allergen, leading to symptoms like dyshydrotic eczema.

diagnoses.name: Upper Respiratory Infections
diagnoses.description: Infections that can affect the nose, throat, and airways, leading to symptoms such as laryngitis.

diagnoses.name: ACE Inhibitor-induced Angioedema
diagnoses.description: Angioedema that is specifically caused by taking ACE inhibitors, a type of medication used to treat high blood pressure and heart failure.

diagnoses.name: Hypereosinophilic Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by an extremely high eosinophil count in the blood and/or tissues, causing a variety of symptoms including dyshydrotic eczema and angioedema.

diagnoses.name: Leukemia
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer of the blood or bone marrow characterized by an abnormal proliferation of blood cells, typically white blood cells. It can lead to symptoms like easy bruising.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the blood vessels become inflamed, potentially causing a range of symptoms including easy bruising and skin rashes.

symptoms: dyspnea with normal pulmonary function tests

diagnoses: Autoimmune Disorders (e.g., Systemic Lupus Erythematosus, Sjögren's Syndrome)

diagnoses.name: Chronic Myeloid Leukemia
diagnoses.description: Chronic Myeloid Leukemia (CML) is a type of cancer that starts in the blood-forming cells of the bone marrow and invades the blood. It can lead to an increased number of white blood cells (leukocytosis), which may indirectly affect puberty timing, contribute to abnormal electrolyte balances, and, less commonly, result in vascular anomalies.

diagnoses.name: Klinefelter Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Klinefelter syndrome is a genetic condition affecting males. Males with this condition typically have an extra X chromosome. Symptoms can include delayed puberty. While leukocytosis, abnormal electrolytes, and vascular anomalies are not hallmark symptoms, individuals with Klinefelter syndrome may have varied health issues including those affecting the endocrine system.

diagnoses.name: Turner Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Turner Syndrome is a chromosomal disorder affecting females, where one of the X chromosomes is missing or partially missing. It can lead to delayed puberty among other symptoms. While leukocytosis, abnormal electrolytes, and vascular anomalies are more indirectly related, cardiovascular anomalies are common.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: Hypothyroidism, often caused by autoimmune disease, can lead to delayed puberty due to hormonal imbalances. It can also contribute to abnormal electrolytes. Leukocytosis is not directly associated, but the broad spectrum of symptoms can include changes in blood count.

diagnoses.name: Myeloproliferative Disorders
diagnoses.description: Myeloproliferative disorders are a group of diseases that involve excess production of blood cells by the bone marrow. This can directly lead to leukocytosis and may have links to delayed puberty and abnormal electrolytes through systemic effects, including vascular anomalies.

diagnoses.name: Adrenal Hyperplasia
diagnoses.description: Congenital adrenal hyperplasia (CAH) involves a group of inherited disorders that affect the adrenal glands. It can lead to abnormal electrolyte levels and delayed puberty. Leukocytosis and vascular anomalies may not be direct symptoms but can appear in severe or poorly managed cases.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.description: While primarily affecting blood sugar control, diabetes mellitus can indirectly cause delayed puberty and abnormal electrolyte levels. Poorly managed diabetes can contribute to vascular anomalies due to prolonged high blood sugar levels.

diagnoses.name: Anorexia Nervosa
diagnoses.description: An eating disorder characterized by an abnormally low body weight, fear of gaining weight, and a distorted perception of weight. It can lead to delayed puberty and abnormal electrolytes. While not directly causing leukocytosis or vascular anomalies, severe anorexia can lead to a wide range of secondary health issues.

diagnoses.name: Malnutrition
diagnoses.description: Malnutrition refers to getting too little or too much of certain nutrients. It can cause delayed puberty and abnormal electrolytes. While leukocytosis is not a primary symptom, malnutrition can lead to various systemic issues, potentially affecting the vascular system.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.description: Chronic kidney disease (CKD) affects kidney function over time. It's known to cause abnormalities in electrolyte levels and can contribute to delayed puberty. While leukocytosis isn't a direct symptom, the systemic nature of CKD can lead to a range of complications, including issues related to the vascular system.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Strokes may cause symptoms such as paralysis, speech difficulties, and time-dependent goings such as headaches.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: Migraines are a neurological condition that can cause multiple symptoms. It's frequently characterized by intense, debilitating headaches. Symptoms may include nausea, vomiting, difficulty speaking, numbness or tingling, and sensitivity to light and sound.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.description: Often called a ministroke, a transient ischemic attack is a brief, temporary disruption of blood supply to part of the brain, spinal cord, or retina, which may cause symptoms similar to those of a stroke.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A brain tumor is a mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. Many different types of brain tumors exist. Some brain tumors are noncancerous (benign), and some brain tumors are cancerous (malignant). Headaches, speech or hearing problems, and numbness or tingling can be symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a potentially disabling disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system). The immune system attacks the protective sheath (myelin) that covers nerve fibers, causing communication problems between your brain and the rest of your body.

diagnoses.name: Brain Abscess
diagnoses.description: A brain abscess is a collection of pus that develops in response to an infection or trauma. It can cause headaches, fever, weakness, seizures, and changes in behavior or speech.

diagnoses.name: Temporal Arteritis
diagnoses.description: Temporal arteritis is an inflammation of the blood vessels, usually those in the temples, which can cause persistent headaches, vision disturbances, and sometimes symptoms like scalp tenderness. It typically occurs in older adults.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's Disease
diagnoses.description: Meniere's disease affects the inner ear and can cause dizziness, tinnitus, hearing loss, and a feeling of pressure in the ear. Though not directly related to aphasia or numbness, its symptoms can overlap with other neurological conditions.

diagnoses.name: Acoustic Neuroma
diagnoses.description: An acoustic neuroma is a noncancerous growth that develops on the vestibular nerve, which connects the inner ear to the brain. Main symptoms include hearing loss, tinnitus, and balance problems. It can also affect facial muscles.

diagnoses.name: Intracerebral Hemorrhage
diagnoses.description: This condition involves bleeding within the brain tissue itself, which can be life-threatening. Symptoms can include headache, nausea, vomiting, numbness or weakness, and difficulty with speech or understanding language.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.reason: SLE can manifest with a wide range of symptoms including malar rash, pleural effusion, thrombocytopenia, hemolytic anemia, and potentially chilblains (in cases of Raynaud's phenomenon associated with lupus).

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.reason: MCTD shares features with systemic lupus erythematosus, scleroderma, and polymyositis, including manifestations such as raynaud's phenomenon which may present as chilblains, as well as possible malar rash, pleural effusion, and hematological abnormalities including thrombocytopenia and hemolytic anemia.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis (RA) with Felty's Syndrome
diagnoses.reason: RA primarily affects the joints, but Felty's syndrome, a rare complication, can include thrombocytopenia and anemia, along with potential pleural effusions.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.reason: Though more commonly associated with dry eyes and dry mouth, Sjögren's syndrome can also cause systemic complications. Raynaud's phenomenon could present as chilblains. There is also potential for overlap with other connective tissue diseases, leading to symptoms such as pleural effusion and hematological abnormalities.

diagnoses.name: Evans Syndrome
diagnoses.reason: This rare autoimmune disorder is characterized by the combination of immune thrombocytopenia (ITP) and autoimmune hemolytic anemia, potentially alongside other autoimmune symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Antiphospholipid Syndrome (APS)
diagnoses.reason: APS can cause thrombocytopenia and is associated with systemic autoimmune conditions like SLE, potentially presenting with symptoms such as malar rash.

diagnoses.name: Idiopathic Thrombocytopenic Purpura (ITP)
diagnoses.reason: While primarily known for causing thrombocytopenia, ITP can occur in conjunction with other autoimmune disorders, potentially linking to conditions with symptoms like hemolytic anemia or pleural effusion.

diagnoses.name: Anemia of Chronic Disease
diagnoses.reason: Though not a direct cause of the symptoms listed, anemia of chronic disease can occur alongside chronic inflammatory conditions that might present with pleural effusion, thrombocytopenia, or autoimmune features.

diagnoses.name: Waldenström's Macroglobulinemia
diagnoses.reason: This rare type of cancer affects the blood and can lead to symptoms including anemia, though it's less commonly associated with the full spectrum of symptoms listed.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia (CLL)
diagnoses.reason: Though primarily a cancer of the blood and bone marrow, CLL can cause autoimmune complications, such as autoimmune hemolytic anemia and thrombocytopenia, and may coexist with other conditions leading to the observed symptoms.
